There are a total of 21 studies that have been incorporated into this review. Before the year 2015, there were no studies utilizing learning analytics in virtual labs. All articles were published between 2015 and 2021. The maximum number of studies per year was five articles in 2021 followed by four articles in 2018. The majority of the reviewed articles were presented at conferences (n=12), whereas the remaining nine articles were published in journals (Fig. 2).

**FIGURE 2.** Type and year of the reviewed articles

{{TABLE:tbl_02}}

The reviewed studies have populations from various educational levels (Fig. 3). The majority of the research in the reviewed articles (57.1%) was conducted in higher education institutions (n=12) and two of these studies involved postgraduate students in their analysis [W3096149881, W3136757038]. Six studies (28.6%) were conducted on secondary education, and four of them focused on STEM (science, technology, engineering, and math) subjects [W3119919223, W3197977337, W2771904322, W2109979922]. Only two research projects (9.5%) focused on elementary and middle school students [W2916605384, UNMAPPED:87]. Finally, one study was conducted online as a Massive Open Online Course (MOOC) for students of varying education levels [W2740402613].

**FIGURE 3.** Educational Levels in the reviewed studies

{{TABLE:tbl_03}}

The reviewed studies covered different disciplines of science, medicine, and engineering (Fig. 4). The medical and dental virtual practices were used in practical-based physiology courses [UNMAPPED:90], virtual patient cases [W2891780261], periodontology and oral pathology [W3096149881], and prosthodontics courses [W3100638881, W3206020311]. Chemistry virtual labs were used in concentration experiments [W2797911300] and organic chemistry [W2176167168], while biology labs covered Euglena's interactive live [W2740402613], and molecular biology experiments [W2176167168]. Virtual labs for science classes were available for school students [W2916605384, UNMAPPED:87] and students in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) [W3119919223, W3197977337, W2109979922, W2109979922]. Virtual labs were used in different fields of computer science, namely Java programming [W2550135895], cloud applications [W2559606780], and network virtual labs [W2752444842]. The engineering virtual labs covered automotive engineering [W2907646290], container-based virtual labs [W2986200109], and building electrical circuits [W3136757038]. Other practices include digital electronic simulation environments [W3136757038] and remote labs in the field of image processing [W2280291775].

